00:00:00.390 --> 00:00:02.650
 Here I have an interesting system, 

00:00:02.650 --> 00:00:06.300
 I have two compartments - in the left compartment I have gas, 

00:00:06.300 --> 00:00:09.750
 which has a temperature of T with index a, 

00:00:09.750 --> 00:00:14.900
 and on the right side I have a gas that has a temperature T with index b. 

00:00:14.940 --> 00:00:19.320
 They are separated by a wall of depth d, 

00:00:19.320 --> 00:00:22.020
 or suppose you can say in thickness d. 

00:00:22.020 --> 00:00:24.980
 And the contact area of ​​the wall, 

00:00:24.980 --> 00:00:27.820
 or the contact area of ​​the gas with the wall, 

00:00:27.820 --> 00:00:30.580
 this area is A - and draw only part of it, 

00:00:30.580 --> 00:00:34.740
 we assume that these two compartments are completely separated. 

00:00:34.740 --> 00:00:36.940
 Now I'm curious - and we will accept, 

00:00:36.940 --> 00:00:40.920
 that the temperature on the left is higher than the temperature on the right 

00:00:40.940 --> 00:00:44.140
 and therefore you will have a heat transfer 

00:00:44.140 --> 00:00:45.840
 from left to right. 

00:00:45.840 --> 00:00:49.020
 And the heat that is transferred is called heat 

00:00:49.020 --> 00:00:51.320
 and we will label it with the letter Q. 

00:00:51.320 --> 00:00:54.560
 I wonder how the speed at which heat is transferred, 

00:00:54.560 --> 00:00:57.260
 or how much heat is transferred per unit of time - 

00:00:57.260 --> 00:00:59.080
 this is the rate at which heat is transferred - 

00:00:59.090 --> 00:01:01.150
 how this will change, depending on it 

00:01:01.150 --> 00:01:03.680
 how we change these different variables. 

00:01:03.680 --> 00:01:10.020
 For example, if our contact area increases, 

00:01:10.020 --> 00:01:13.140
 what will this do for Q / t? 

00:01:13.150 --> 00:01:16.490
 Then Q / t will also increase for a unit of time, 

00:01:16.490 --> 00:01:19.520
 because I have more space, 

00:01:19.520 --> 00:01:22.960
 in which these hot air particles or molecules 

00:01:22.960 --> 00:01:25.080
 can crash, and heat that wall. 

00:01:25.080 --> 00:01:26.820
 And then there will be a more heated wall, 

00:01:26.820 --> 00:01:29.890
 which will heat up the colder air particles. 

00:01:29.890 --> 00:01:34.120
 That is, in this case, the rate of heat transfer will also increase. 

00:01:34.120 --> 00:01:38.260
 And obviously, if I make my area smaller - 

00:01:38.260 --> 00:01:40.520
 maybe I have to explicitly write down this - 

00:01:40.520 --> 00:01:43.820
 and if I make my contact area smaller, 

00:01:43.820 --> 00:01:46.880
 then my heat transfer rate will decrease 

00:01:46.880 --> 00:01:49.520
 and this seems to be self-explanatory. 

00:01:49.520 --> 00:01:52.320
 And what about thickness? 

00:01:52.320 --> 00:01:55.520
 If you increase the thickness, 

00:01:55.520 --> 00:01:57.140
 if I make this wall thicker, 

00:01:57.150 --> 00:01:59.490
 what will it do with my transfer rate of heat? 

00:01:59.490 --> 00:02:02.440
 Then I will have more things to warm up, 

00:02:02.440 --> 00:02:06.480
 to make them with a certain temperature, 

00:02:06.520 --> 00:02:09.600
 which can then heat the particles to the right 

00:02:09.600 --> 00:02:11.240
 and obviously this is a continuous process - 

00:02:11.250 --> 00:02:14.300
 it will always be done, but there will be more things to heat up. 

00:02:14.300 --> 00:02:19.000
 And it will take more and more of this kinetic energy, 

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:22.500
 this average kinetic energy will be displaced in this wall, 

00:02:22.500 --> 00:02:25.200
 if this wall becomes thicker. 

00:02:25.210 --> 00:02:27.200
 If the wall gets thicker, 

00:02:27.200 --> 00:02:30.150
 then the heat transfer rate will decrease. 

00:02:30.150 --> 00:02:34.380
 Or if the wall becomes thinner, if this depth is reduced, 

00:02:34.380 --> 00:02:39.200
 then the heat transfer rate will increase. 

00:02:39.200 --> 00:02:41.120
 That is, you can say that the speed of heat transfer 

00:02:41.120 --> 00:02:45.820
 will be inversely proportional to the thickness of the wall. 

00:02:45.820 --> 00:02:47.840
 What else can we think of? 

00:02:47.850 --> 00:02:51.450
 Well, for the differential temperature. 

00:02:51.450 --> 00:03:00.100
 This is T with index a minus T with index b. 

